Tests still pass. The task list isn't relevant for this small refactoring (a single Refactor subagent invocation). Let me now consider further refactoring of `itemsBaseSum`.

Current `itemsBaseSum`:
```typescript
const itemsBaseSum = (items: Item[]): number => {
  let mainBase = 0;
  const componentCounts = new Map<string, number>();
  for (const item of items) {
    const type = item.type as string;
    if (COMPONENT_TYPES.has(type)) {
      componentCounts.set(type, (componentCounts.get(type) ?? 0) + 1);
    } else {
      mainBase += itemBasePremium(item);
    }
  }
  let componentBase = 0;
  for (const [type, count] of componentCounts) {
    componentBase += componentGroupBase(count, BASE_PREMIUM_BY_TYPE[type] ?? 0);
  }
  return mainBase + componentBase;
};
```

I could refactor this into two clearer phases — grouping then summing — using functional style. But the current code is reasonably clear and the upcoming tests (4 runes, 7 runes, 2 runes + 1 moonstone, 3 runes + 3 moonstones) all use this same structure. Restructuring further risks breaking the clean partitioning of components vs main items.

Let me consider a more focused improvement: splitting `itemsBaseSum` to clarify the two phases (group, then sum each group). This would improve Rule 2 (Intent).

